{"key":"processedPost-13226393","value":{"id":13226393,"first":13225470,"last":13226497,"when":1285086827,"utime":"09/21/10 07:33 PM","content":"It's OK if the water touches the bottoms of the jars as already said.&nbsp; The reason Roadkill and I said not to in the DVD is because so many people put too much water in, and then it splashes over the top and gets into the jars, ruining moisture content.<br /><br />However, if you're careful and monitor the process as you should rather than getting stoned and playing video games during sterilization, you'll be fine.&nbsp; Once the water boils and steam begins escaping from under the lid, turn down the stove to the lowest setting that will keep that steam escaping.&nbsp; The danger from leaving the stove on high is two fold-First, the pot can boil dry, and second, the water can splash over the jars as it boils, screwing up the moisture.&nbsp; If you're attentive as you should be, neither of these are problems, but we wanted to make the video as idiot proof as possible.<br />RR","title":"Re: Concerning steam sterilization . . .","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}